{"title_page": "Randall Woodfin", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Randall Woodfin\n|image       = Randall Woodfin - 2019.jpg\n|office      = 34th [[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]\n|term_start  = November 28, 2017\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[William A. Bell]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1981|5|29}}\n|birth_place = [[Birmingham, Alabama]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education   = [[Morehouse College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Samford University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website     = {{url|randallwoodfin.com|Campaign website}}\n}}\n'''Randall Woodfin''' (born May 29, 1981) is an American lawyer and politician who is the 34th and current [[Mayor of Birmingham, Alabama|mayor of]] [[Birmingham, Alabama]], after winning the October 3, 2017, runoff against incumbent [[William A. Bell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/10/randall_woodfin_wins_birmingha.html|title=Randall Woodfin wins Birmingham mayor's race: What they're saying nationally|work=AL.com|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref> He previously served as the President of the Birmingham City School Board (2013\u20132015) and as an Assistant City Attorney for the City of Birmingham since 2009.\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nBorn and raised in Birmingham, Woodfin attended [[Shades Valley High School]] and [[Morehouse College]], where he majored in political science and served as president of Student Government Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/world/this-morehouse-alum-just-became-the-youngest-mayor-birmingham-modern-history/s0co6Rwv6D2KRIOpLUdPLK/|title=This Morehouse alum just became the youngest mayor of Birmingham in modern history|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|last=Najja Parker|website=ajc}}</ref> Woodfin went on to earn his law degree from the [[Cumberland School of Law]] at [[Samford University]].\n\n==Pre-Mayorship==\nUpon graduating from law school, Woodfin served as a public servant working with the city's Division of Youth Services, the Birmingham City Council, and the Jefferson County Committee for Economic Opportunity (JCCEO). In 2009, Randall became an Assistant City Attorney for the City of Birmingham. During the same time frame, Randall ran for a seat on the Birmingham City Schools Board of Education.  In 2013, Woodfin was not only successful in his second attempt to secure his seat on the school board, but he was also elected President, a role he served from 2013-2015.\n\nWoodfin also served as a board member of other community organizations, including the Alabama Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy, [[Birmingham Botanical Gardens (United States)|Birmingham Botanical Gardens]], and the Hispanic Interest Coalition of Alabama. He is a former board member of Birmingham Change Fund, American Red Cross, Birmingham Education Foundation, Birmingham Cultural Alliance, S.T.A.I.R., and past President of the Birmingham chapter of the Morehouse College Alumni Association. Woodfin is a graduate of Leadership Birmingham class of 2014, Leadership Alabama class of 2016, and served as a featured speaker at [[TEDx]] Birmingham 2017.\n\n==2017 Mayoral Campaign==\nWoodfin announced his run for Birmingham mayor in August 2016, challenging incumbent candidate William Bell along with 10 other candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/news/2016/08/22/assistant-city-attorney-to-run-for-mayor.html|title=Assistant city attorney to run for mayor|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In the [[2017 Birmingham, Alabama mayoral election|general election]], held on August 22, 2017, Woodfin won 40% of the vote, triggering a runoff election with Bell, who placed second. Woodfin won the October 3 runoff with 58.95% of the vote. \n\nDuring the campaign, Woodfin criticized Bell's failure to improve Birmingham residents' quality of life<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wbhm.org/feature/2017/tuesday-runoff-election-pits-bell-vs-woodfin/|title=In Tuesday's Mayoral Runoff, Bell Touts Experience, Woodfin Pushes Change|website=WBHM 90.3|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and promised to focus his administration on revitalization of the city's 99 neighborhoods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/10/people_want_change.html|title=Randall Woodfin defeats William Bell in mayor's race|date=2017-10-04|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Mayorship==\n[[Image:Randall Woodfin.jpg|thumb|left|Woodfin speaks at a town hall meeting in January 2019.]] In March 2018, Woodfin's transition committee announced it had discovered that the city's pension fund had been consistently underfunded for more than 15 years, endangering the city's credit rating and retirement benefits for thousands of city employees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/hole-balance-sheet-birminghams-impending-pension-crisis/|title=A Hole in the Balance Sheet: Birmingham\u2019s Impending Pension Crisis|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2018-04-16|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin increased funding to the pension fund by $2.9 million in the city's 2019 budget, and by $5.2 million in the city's 2020 budget \u2014 which Woodfin's administration claimed fully met the city's obligation to the fund for the first time in more than a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/woodfin-highlights-moral-obligations-proposed-2020-budget/|title=Woodfin Highlights \u201cMoral Obligations\u201d of Proposed 2020 Budget|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2019-05-14|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin's administration has drawn criticism for a perceived lack of transparency, with [[AL.com]] columnist Kyle Whitmire calling Woodfin's attempts to block public information requests \"stalling and stonewalling\" and a violation of his campaign promises to increase transparency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/09/whats-randall-woodfin-hiding.html|title=Whitmire: What's Randall Woodfin hiding?|date=2019-09-06|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin endorsed [[Joe Biden]] in the [[2020 Democratic presidential primary]], despite having received [[Bernie Sanders]]' endorsement during his 2017 mayoral race. Woodfin cited Biden's ability to \"make sure down-ballot candidates can win\" as a primary reason for his endorsement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/12/birmingham-mayor-randall-woodfin-endorses-sen-joe-biden-in-2020-presidential-race.html|title=Woodfin makes endorsement in 2020 Democratic presidential race|date=2019-12-16|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nBirmingham's high violent crime rate was a priority for Woodfin's campaign; Woodfin's nephew, Ralph Woodfin III, was shot and killed in August 2017, during Woodfin's mayoral campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/08/tarrant_police_investigate_hom.html|title=Teen killed in Tarrant shooting was Birmingham mayoral candidate's nephew|work=AL.com|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Woodfin took office in November 2017, Birmingham Police Department Chief A.C. Roper announced his resignation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/police-chief-c-roper-retires-mayor-woodfin-looks-make-personnel-changes-city-hall/|title=Police Chief A.C. Roper Retires as Mayor Woodfin Looks to Make Personnel Changes at City Hall|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2017-11-29|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> After a lengthy search, Woodfin appointed former [[Los Angeles Police Department]] commander Patrick D. Smith to the position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/birmingham-hires-la-commander-new-police-chief/|title=Birmingham Hires LA Commander to be New Police Chief|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2018-06-04|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Woodfin's administration unveiled a public service announcement campaign titled \"PEACE\" featuring 30-second videos of mothers of gun violence victims telling their stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghamal.gov/2019/02/28/mayor-woodfin-unveils-peace-campaign-to-counteract-violent-crime/|title=Mayor Woodfin unveils PEACE Campaign to counteract violent crime|date=2019-02-28|website=The Official Website for the City of Birmingham, Alabama|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nThe city's homicide rate has stayed approximately the same since Woodfin took office; the city logged 117 homicides in 2017, 110 in 2018, and 112 in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhamwiki.com/w/Birmingham_homicides_by_year#2010s|title=Birmingham homicides by year - Bhamwiki|website=www.bhamwiki.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin has maintained that total violent crime has dropped in the city during his tenure, and points to the police department's removal of thousands of guns from the streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/07/birmingham-mayor-woodfin-gives-state-city-address/|title=Birmingham Mayor Woodfin gives State of the City address|last=Groover|first=Shilo|website=https://www.wbrc.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons inline}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Randall Woodfin}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William A. Bell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Alabama cities and mayors of 100,000 population |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodfin, Randall}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American mayors]]\n[[Category:African-American people in Alabama politics]]\n[[Category:Alabama Democrats]]\n[[Category:Cumberland School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American lawyers]]\n[[Category:Alabama lawyers]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Randall Woodfin\n|image       = Randall Woodfin - 2019.jpg\n|office      = 34th [[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]\n|term_start  = November 28, 2017\n|term_end    = \n|predecessor = [[William A. Bell]]\n|successor   = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1981|5|29}}\n|birth_place = [[Birmingham, Alabama]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education   = [[Morehouse College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Samford University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website     = {{url|randallwoodfin.com|Campaign website}}\n}}\n'''Randall Woodfin''' (born May 29, 1981) is an American lawyer and politician who is the 34th and current [[Mayor of Birmingham, Alabama|mayor of]] [[Birmingham, Alabama]], after winning the October 3, 2017, runoff against incumbent [[William A. Bell]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/10/randall_woodfin_wins_birmingha.html|title=Randall Woodfin wins Birmingham mayor's race: What they're saying nationally|work=AL.com|access-date=2017-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref> He previously served as the President of the Birmingham City School Board (2013\u20132015) and as an Assistant City Attorney for the City of Birmingham since 2009.\n\n==Early Life and Education==\nBorn and raised in Birmingham, Woodfin attended [[Shades Valley High School]] and [[Morehouse College]], where he majored in political science and served as president of Student Government Association.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/world/this-morehouse-alum-just-became-the-youngest-mayor-birmingham-modern-history/s0co6Rwv6D2KRIOpLUdPLK/|title=This Morehouse alum just became the youngest mayor of Birmingham in modern history|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|last=Najja Parker|website=ajc}}</ref> Woodfin went on to earn his law degree from the [[Cumberland School of Law]] at [[Samford University]].\n\n==Pre-Mayorship==\nUpon graduating from law school, Woodfin served as a public servant working with the city's Division of Youth Services, the Birmingham City Council, and the Jefferson County Committee for Economic Opportunity (JCCEO). In 2009, Randall became an Assistant City Attorney for the City of Birmingham. During the same time frame, Randall ran for a seat on the Birmingham City Schools Board of Education.  In 2013, Woodfin was not only successful in his second attempt to secure his seat on the school board, but he was also elected President, a role he served from 2013-2015.\n\nWoodfin also served as a board member of other community organizations, including the Alabama Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy, [[Birmingham Botanical Gardens (United States)|Birmingham Botanical Gardens]], and the Hispanic Interest Coalition of Alabama. He is a former board member of Birmingham Change Fund, American Red Cross, Birmingham Education Foundation, Birmingham Cultural Alliance, S.T.A.I.R., and past President of the Birmingham chapter of the Morehouse College Alumni Association. Woodfin is a graduate of Leadership Birmingham class of 2014, Leadership Alabama class of 2016, and served as a featured speaker at [[TEDx]] Birmingham 2017.\n\n==2017 Mayoral Campaign==\nWoodfin announced his run for Birmingham mayor in August 2016, challenging incumbent candidate William Bell along with 10 other candidates.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/birmingham/news/2016/08/22/assistant-city-attorney-to-run-for-mayor.html|title=Assistant city attorney to run for mayor|website=www.bizjournals.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> In the [[2017 Birmingham, Alabama mayoral election|general election]], held on August 22, 2017, Woodfin won 40% of the vote, triggering a runoff election with Bell, who placed second. Woodfin won the October 3 runoff with 58.95% of the vote. \n\nDuring the campaign, Woodfin criticized Bell's failure to improve Birmingham residents' quality of life<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wbhm.org/feature/2017/tuesday-runoff-election-pits-bell-vs-woodfin/|title=In Tuesday's Mayoral Runoff, Bell Touts Experience, Woodfin Pushes Change|website=WBHM 90.3|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> and promised to focus his administration on revitalization of the city's 99 neighborhoods.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/10/people_want_change.html|title=Randall Woodfin defeats William Bell in mayor's race|date=2017-10-04|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==Mayorship==\n[[Image:Randall Woodfin.jpg|thumb|left|Woodfin speaks at a town hall meeting in January 2019.]] In March 2018, Woodfin's transition committee announced it had discovered that the city's pension fund had been consistently underfunded for more than 15 years, endangering the city's credit rating and retirement benefits for thousands of city employees.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/hole-balance-sheet-birminghams-impending-pension-crisis/|title=A Hole in the Balance Sheet: Birmingham\u2019s Impending Pension Crisis|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2018-04-16|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin increased funding to the pension fund by $2.9 million in the city's 2019 budget, and by $5.2 million in the city's 2020 budget \u2014 which Woodfin's administration claimed fully met the city's obligation to the fund for the first time in more than a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/woodfin-highlights-moral-obligations-proposed-2020-budget/|title=Woodfin Highlights \u201cMoral Obligations\u201d of Proposed 2020 Budget|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2019-05-14|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin's administration has drawn criticism for a perceived lack of transparency, with [[AL.com]] columnist Kyle Whitmire calling Woodfin's attempts to block public information requests \"stalling and stonewalling\" and a violation of his campaign promises to increase transparency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/09/whats-randall-woodfin-hiding.html|title=Whitmire: What's Randall Woodfin hiding?|date=2019-09-06|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nWoodfin endorsed [[Joe Biden]] in the [[2020 Democratic presidential primary]], despite having received [[Bernie Sanders]]' endorsement during his 2017 mayoral race. Woodfin cited Biden's ability to \"make sure down-ballot candidates can win' as a primary reason for his endorsement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/2019/12/birmingham-mayor-randall-woodfin-endorses-sen-joe-biden-in-2020-presidential-race.html|title=Woodfin makes endorsement in 2020 Democratic presidential race|date=2019-12-16|website=al|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n===Crime===\nBirmingham's high violent crime rate was a priority for Woodfin's campaign; Woodfin's nephew, Ralph Woodfin III, was shot and killed in August 2017, during Woodfin's mayoral campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2017/08/tarrant_police_investigate_hom.html|title=Teen killed in Tarrant shooting was Birmingham mayoral candidate's nephew|work=AL.com|access-date=2020-04-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nShortly after Woodfin took office in November 2017, Birmingham Police Department Chief A.C. Roper announced his resignation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/police-chief-c-roper-retires-mayor-woodfin-looks-make-personnel-changes-city-hall/|title=Police Chief A.C. Roper Retires as Mayor Woodfin Looks to Make Personnel Changes at City Hall|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2017-11-29|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> After a lengthy search, Woodfin appointed former [[Los Angeles Police Department]] commander Patrick D. Smith to the position.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://birminghamwatch.org/birmingham-hires-la-commander-new-police-chief/|title=Birmingham Hires LA Commander to be New Police Chief|last=Prickett|first=Sam|date=2018-06-04|website=BirminghamWatch|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Woodfin's administration unveiled a public service announcement campaign titled \"PEACE\" featuring 30-second videos of mothers of gun violence victims telling their stories.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.birminghamal.gov/2019/02/28/mayor-woodfin-unveils-peace-campaign-to-counteract-violent-crime/|title=Mayor Woodfin unveils PEACE Campaign to counteract violent crime|date=2019-02-28|website=The Official Website for the City of Birmingham, Alabama|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\nThe city's homicide rate has stayed approximately the same since Woodfin took office; the city logged 117 homicides in 2017, 110 in 2018, and 112 in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhamwiki.com/w/Birmingham_homicides_by_year#2010s|title=Birmingham homicides by year - Bhamwiki|website=www.bhamwiki.com|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Woodfin has maintained that total violent crime has dropped in the city during his tenure, and points to the police department's removal of thousands of guns from the streets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbrc.com/2020/01/07/birmingham-mayor-woodfin-gives-state-city-address/|title=Birmingham Mayor Woodfin gives State of the City address|last=Groover|first=Shilo|website=https://www.wbrc.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commons inline}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Randall Woodfin}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William A. Bell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of mayors of Birmingham, Alabama|Mayor of Birmingham]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Alabama cities and mayors of 100,000 population |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Woodfin, Randall}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:African-American mayors]]\n[[Category:African-American people in Alabama politics]]\n[[Category:Alabama Democrats]]\n[[Category:Cumberland School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Morehouse College alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American lawyers]]\n[[Category:Alabama lawyers]]\n", "name_user": "Depressed Marvin", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMayorship", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randall_Woodfin"}
{"title_page": "Goethe University Frankfurt", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Goethe University\n| native_name = Goethe-Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main\n| native_name_lang = deu\n| image = Logo-Goethe-University-Frankfurt-am-Main.svg\n| former_name = K\u00f6nigliche Universit\u00e4t zu Frankfurt am Main<ref name=\"2014_Neujahrsempfang\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/49212620/2014_Neujahrsempfang_StadtFrankfurt-Rede_Praesident.pdf |title=\"Aus der Mitte der Stadtgesellschaft \u2013 100 Jahre Goethe-Universit\u00e4t\" von Prof. Dr. Werner M\u00fcller-Esterl |language=German |accessdate=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n| established = {{start date|1914|10|18|df=y}}<ref name=\"2014_Neujahrsempfang\" />\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| budget = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 644.6&nbsp;Mio. <small>''(2018)''</small><ref name=\"jahresbericht_2018\">{{cite web|url=http://www.muk.uni-frankfurt.de/82141680.pdf |title=Jahrbuch 2018. \"Entwicklung gestalten\" |language=German |accessdate=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n| chancellor = [[Albrecht Fester]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muk.uni-frankfurt.de/70896808/060 |title=Goethe-Universit\u00e4t hat neuen Kanzler: Dr. Albrecht Fester \u00fcbernimmt das Amt an Hessens gr\u00f6\u00dfter Universit\u00e4t |language=German |date=2018-03-16 |accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n| president = [[Birgitta Wolff]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/36994074/praesidentin |title=Pr\u00e4sidentin der Goethe-Universit\u00e4t |language=German |accessdate=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n| vice-president = [[Simone Fulda]], [[Rolf van Dick]], [[Roger Erb]], [[Manfred Schubert-Zsilavecz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/36994091/vizepraesidenten |title=Vizepr\u00e4sidenten der Goethe-Universit\u00e4t |language=German |accessdate=2018-09-10}}</ref>\n| faculty = 3,055.97 <small>''([[Full-time equivalent|FTE]], 2018)''</small><ref name=\"jahresbericht_2018\" />\n| administrative_staff = 2,038.56 <small>''([[Full-time equivalent|FTE]], 2018)''</small><ref name=\"jahresbericht_2018\" />\n| students = 46,325 <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uni-frankfurt.de/52565158 |title=Studierendenstatistik (Daten pro Semester) |language=German |accessdate=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n| undergrad = 21,366 <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\" />\n| postgrad = 7,169 <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\" />\n| doctoral = 1,664 <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\" />\n| other = 6,279 ([[teacher education]]) <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\" />\n| address = <small>Campus Westend:</small><br />Theodor-W.-Adorno-Platz&nbsp;1\n| city = [[Frankfurt am Main]]\n| state = [[Hessen]]\n| country = Germany\n| postcode = 60323\n| coor = {{Coord|50|7|40|N|8|40|00|E|type:edu_region:DE|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = multiple sites\n| language = [[German language|German]]\n| website = {{URL|1=http://www.goethe-university-frankfurt.de/|2=www.goethe-university-frankfurt.de}}\n| logo = HouseofFinance.jpg\n}}\n'''Goethe University''' ({{lang-de|Goethe-Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main}}) is a [[university]] located in [[Frankfurt am Main]], Germany. It was founded in 1914 as a citizens' university, which means it was founded and funded by the wealthy and active liberal citizenry of Frankfurt. The original name was '''Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main'''. In 1932, the university's name was extended in honour of one of the most famous native sons of Frankfurt, the poet, philosopher and writer/dramatist [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]. The university currently has around 45,000 students, distributed across four major campuses within the city.\n\nThe university celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2014. The first female president of the university, [[Birgitta Wolff]], was sworn into office in 2015.<ref name=\"Neue Uni-Pr\u00e4sidentin will kommunikativen F\u00fchrungsstil\">{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/rhein-main/frankfurt/frankfurt-neue-uni-praesidentin-birgitta-wolff-will-kommunikativen-fuehrungsstil-13319493.html|title=Neue Uni-Pr\u00e4sidentin will kommunikativen F\u00fchrungsstil|accessdate=2015-03-03|newspaper=Faz.net}}</ref> 20 [[List of Nobel laureates by university affiliation|Nobel Prize winners]] have been [[List of Nobel laureates by university affiliation#Other universities|affiliated with the university]], including [[Max von Laue]] and [[Max Born]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1914/laue.html|title=Nobel prize Physics laureates}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/39246655/nobelpreis?|title=Goethe-Universit\u00e4t \u2014 Nobelpreistr\u00e4ger an der Goethe Universit\u00e4t|website=www.uni-frankfurt.de|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> The university is also affiliated with 18 winners of the prestigious [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/39246641/leibnizpreis?|title=Goethe-Universit\u00e4t \u2014 Leibnizpreistr\u00e4ger an der Goethe-Universit\u00e4t|website=www.uni-frankfurt.de|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nGoethe University is part of the [[IT cluster Rhine-Main-Neckar]]. The [[Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz]], the Goethe University Frankfurt and the [[Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt]] together form the [[Rhine-Main-Universities]] (RMU).\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F005759-0014, Frankfurt-Main, Universit\u00e4t.jpg|thumb|Campus Bockenheim (in 1958)]]\n\nThe historical roots of the university can be traced back as far as 1484, when a City Council Library was established with a bequest from the patrician Ludwig von Marburg. Merged with other collections, it was renamed City Library in 1668 and became the university library in 1914. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ub.uni-frankfurt.de/ueber/stub_geschichte.html|title=Geschichte der Stadt- und Universit\u00e4tsbibliothek|website=www.ub.uni-frankfurt.de|access-date=2017-08-05}}</ref> Depending on the country, the date of foundation is recorded differently. According to Anglo-American calculations, the founding date of Goethe University would be 1484. In Germany, the date on which the right to award doctorates is granted is considered the founding year of a university.\n\nThe university has been best known historically for its [[Institute for Social Research]] (founded 1924), the institutional home of the [[Frankfurt School]], a preeminent 20th century school of [[philosophy]] and social thought. Some of the well-known scholars associated with this school include [[Theodor Adorno]], [[Max Horkheimer]], and [[J\u00fcrgen Habermas]], as well as [[Herbert Marcuse]], [[Erich Fromm]], and [[Walter Benjamin]] {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. Other well-known scholars at the University of Frankfurt include the sociologist [[Karl Mannheim]], the philosopher [[Hans-Georg Gadamer]], the philosophers of religion [[Franz Rosenzweig]], [[Martin Buber]], and [[Paul Tillich]], the psychologist [[Max Wertheimer]], and the sociologist [[Norbert Elias]] {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}.\nThe University of Frankfurt has at times been considered liberal, or left-leaning, and has had a reputation for [[Jew]]ish and [[Marxist]] (or even Jewish-Marxist) scholarship {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. During the [[Nazism|Nazi]] period, \"almost one third of its academics and many of its students were dismissed for racial and/or political reasons\u2014more than at any other German university\" {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. The university also played a major part in the [[German student movement]] of 1968.\n\nThe university also has been influential in the natural sciences and medicine, with Nobel Prize winners including [[Max von Laue]] and [[Max Born]], and breakthroughs such as the [[Stern\u2013Gerlach experiment]].\n\nIn recent years, the university has focused in particular on law, history, and economics, creating new institutes, such as the [[Institute for Law and Finance]] (ILF) and the [[Center for Financial Studies]] (CFS) {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. One of the university's ambitions is to become Germany's leading university for finance and economics, given the school's proximity to one of Europe's financial centers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finance.uni-frankfurt.de/master/presse/178.pdf |title=Die Johann Wolfgang Goethe-Universit\u00e4t auf dem Weg zur f\u00fchrenden Wirtschaftshochschule in Deutschland |date= |accessdate=2011-09-26}}</ref> In cooperation with [[Duke University]]\u2019s [[Fuqua School of Business]], the [[Goethe Business School]] offers an [[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]] program. Goethe University has established an international award for research in financial economics, the [[Deutsche bank prize|Deutsche Bank Prize in Financial Economics]].\n\n==Organization==\n[[File:Campus-westend-hoersaalgebaeude-hoersaal-2008-10-27-5.jpg|thumb|Campus Westend]]\n[[File:Bibliothek-westend-2005-10-27 1 (1).jpg|thumb|University Library at Campus Westend]]\n\nThe university consists of 16 faculties. Ordered by their sorting number, these are:<ref name=\"\u6cd5\u862d\u514b\u798f\u5927\u5b78\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.uni-frankfurt.de/43171422|title=Faculties|accessdate=2014-05-11}}</ref>\uff1a\n* 01. Rechtswissenschaft (Law)\n* 02. Wirtschaftswissenschaften (Economics and Business Administration)\n* 03. Gesellschaftswissenschaften (Social Sciences)\n* 04. Erziehungswissenschaften (Educational Sciences)\n* 05. Psychologie und Sportwissenschaften (Psychology and Sports Sciences)\n* 06. Evangelische Theologie (Protestant Theology)\n* 07. Katholische Theologie (Roman Catholic Theology)\n* 08. Philosophie und Geschichtswissenschaften (Philosophy and History)\n* 09. Sprach- und Kulturwissenschaften (Faculty of Linguistics, Cultures, and Arts)\n* 10. Neuere Philologien (Modern Languages)\n* 11. Geowissenschaften/Geographie (Geosciences and Geography)\n* 12. Informatik und Mathematik (Computer Science and Mathematics)\n* 13. Physik (Physics)\n* 14. Biochemie, Chemie und Pharmazie (Biochemistry, Chemistry and Pharmacy)\n* 15. Biowissenschaften (Biological Sciences)\n* 16. Medizin (Medical Science)\n\nIn addition, there are several co-located research institutes of the [[Max Planck Society]]:\n* [[Max Planck Institute of Biophysics]]\n* [[Max Planck Institute for Brain Research]]\n* [[Max Planck Institute for European Legal History]]\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Campus Westend Frankfurt 01.jpg|thumb|Campus Westend]]\n[[File:Campus-westend-park-am-poelzig-bau-2008-05-05-2.jpg|thumb|Campus Westend]]\n\nThe University is located across four campuses in Frankfurt am Main:\n\n* '''Campus Westend''': \nHeadquarters of the university, also housing Social sciences, Pedagogy, Psychology, Theology, Philosophy, History, Philology, Archaeology, Law, Economics and Business Administration, Human geography\n\n* '''Campus Bockenheim''': \nUniversity library, Mathematics, Computer science, Art history, Fine Arts\n\n* '''Campus Riedberg''': \nPharmacy, Physics, Chemistry, Biochemistry, Biology, Geosciences and Geography\n\n* '''Campus Niederrad''': \nMedical science, Dentistry, University hospital\n\n* '''Campus Ginnheim:'''\n\nSports.\n\n===Campus Westend===\n[[File:IG Farben Gebaeude Uni Frankfurt.jpg|thumb|[[IG Farben Building]] at Uni Frankfurt|500px]]\n[[File:Goethe University Frankfurt Poelzig Building.jpeg|thumb|[[IG Farben Building]] at ''Campus Westend'']]\n\u201cCampus Westend\u201d of the University is dominated by the [[IG Farben Building]] by architect Hans Poelzig, an example of the [[Modern architecture|modernist]] [[New Objectivity]] style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monumente-online.de/de/ausgaben/2007/5/das-uebertuenchte-arkadien.php|title=Ein Wandgem\u00e4lde in Frankfurts Universit\u00e4t - Monumente Online|website=www.monumente-online.de}}</ref><ref>M. Tafuri, F. Dal Co: Klassische Moderne, Stuttgart, 1988, S148f</ref> The style for the IG Farben Building was originally chosen as \"a symbol for the scientific and mercantile German manpower, made out of iron and stone\", as the [[IG Farben]] director at the time of construction, [[Georg von Schnitzler|Baron von Schnitzler]], stated in his opening speech in October 1930.\n\nAfter the university took over the complex, new buildings were added to the campus. On 30 May 2008, the [[House of Finance]] relocated to a new building designed by the architects Kleihues+Kleihues, following the style of the IG Farben Building. The upper floors of the House of Finance building have several separate offices as well as shared office space for researchers and students. The ground floor is open to the public and welcomes visitors with a spacious, naturally lit foyer that leads to lecture halls, seminar rooms, and the information center, a 24-hour reference library. The ground floor also accommodates computer rooms and a caf\u00e9. The floors, walls and ceiling of the foyer are decorated with a grid design that is continued throughout the entire building. The flooring is inspired by Raphael's mural, ''The School of Athens''.\n\n==Goethe Business School==\nThe [[Goethe Business School]] is a graduate business school at the university, established in 2004, part of the House of Finance at the Westend Campus and the IKB building. it is a non-profit foundation under private law held by the university. The Chairman of the Board at Goethe Business School, Rolf E. Breuer, is former Chairman of the Supervisory Board of [[Deutsche Bank]] {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. Goethe Business School has a partnership in Executive Education with the [[Indian School of Business]] (ISB) in Hyderabad {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}.\n\n==The Deutsche Bank Prize==\nThe [[Deutsche Bank Prize in Financial Economics]] honors renowned researchers who have made influential contributions to the fields of finance and money and macroeconomics, and whose work has led to practical and policy-relevant results. It is awarded biannually, since 2005, by the [[Center for Financial Studies]], in partnership with Goethe University Frankfurt. The award carries an endowment of \u20ac50,000, which is donated by the Stiftungsfonds Deutsche Bank im Stifterverband f\u00fcr die Deutsche Wissenschaft.\n\n==Notable faculty (partial list)==\n* [[Theodor W. Adorno]] (1903\u20131969), double Ordinarius of philosophy and sociology and member of the [[Frankfurt School]]\n* [[Max Horkheimer]], member of the [[Frankfurt School]]\n* [[J\u00fcrgen Habermas]], sociologist and a philosopher\n* [[Hans Bethe]], theoretical physicist (Nobel Prize 1967)\n* [[Max Born]], theoretical physicist and mathematician (Nobel Prize 1954)\n* [[Klaus Bringmann]], historian\n* [[Rolf van Dick]], social psychologist\n* [[Paul Ehrlich]], Nobel Prize Winner 1908\n* [[Walter Gerlach]], theoretical physicist\n* [[Walter Hallstein]] (1901\u20131982), first [[President of the European Commission]]\n* [[Helmut Kiener]], psychologist turned investment professional, founder of the [[ponzi scheme]] [[K1 fund]]\n* [[Vladimir Ko\u0161ak]], economist, lawyer, politician and diplomat\n* [[Josef Mengele]], officer and a physician in the [[Nazi concentration camp]] [[Auschwitz]]\n* [[Oskar Dirlewanger]], officer, who served as the founder and commander of the infamous Nazi SS penal unit \"[[36th Waffen Grenadier Division of the SS|Dirlewanger]]\" during World War II\n* [[Boudewijn Sirks]], Professor of the History of Ancient Law from 1997 to 2005, later [[Regius Professor of Civil Law (Oxford)|Regius Professor of Civil Law]] at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]\n* [[Walter Greiner]], theoretical physicist in high energy physics\n* [[Alfred Schmidt (philosopher)|Alfred Schmidt]], philosopher and translator\n* [[Horst St\u00f6cker]], theoretical physicist\n* [[Alexander R. Todd, Baron Todd]], chemist\n* [[Moses Rothschild]], innovator\n* [[Luciano Rezzolla]], theoretical astrophysicist\n\n==Nobel Prize winners (alumni and faculty)==\n* [[Paul Ehrlich]]: 1908 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\n* [[Max von Laue]]: 1914 Nobel Prize for Physics<ref>{{cite web|title=Nobel Prize Goethe University|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1914/laue.html|accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n* [[Otto Loewi]]: 1914 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine<ref>{{cite web|title=Loewi, Otto|url=http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz54009.html|website=Deutsche Biographie|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Karrer]]: 1937 Nobel Prize for Chemistry\n* [[Otto Stern]]: 1943 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[Max Born]]: 1954 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[Alexander Robertus Todd]]: 1957 Nobel Prize for Chemistry\n* [[Karl Ziegler]]: 1963 Nobel Prize for Chemistry\n* [[Hans Bethe]]: 1967 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[Niels Kaj Jerne]]: 1984 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine<ref name=\"nobellist\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/39246655/nobelpreis|title=Goethe-Universit\u00e4t \u2014 Nobelpreistr\u00e4ger an der Goethe Universit\u00e4t|website=www.uni-frankfurt.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Niels K. Jerne - Biographical|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/1984/jerne-bio.html|accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n* [[Gerd Binnig]]: 1986 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[Jean-Marie Lehn]]: 1987 Nobel Prize for Chemistry<ref name=\"nobellist\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Marie Pierre Lehn - Curriculum Vitae|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1987/lehn-cv.html|accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n* [[Hartmut Michel]]: 1988 Nobel Prize for Chemistry\n* [[Reinhard Selten]]: 1994 Nobel Prize for Economics\n* [[Christiane N\u00fcsslein-Volhard]]: 1995 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\n* [[Horst Ludwig St\u00f6rmer]]: 1998 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[G\u00fcnter Blobel]]: 1999 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\n* [[Peter Gr\u00fcnberg]]: 2007 Nobel Prize for Physics\n\n==World rankings==\n{{Infobox European university ranking\n| ARWU_W = 101-150 | ARWU_W_ref = <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/ARWU2017.html|title=ARWU World University Rankings 2017 &#124; Academic Ranking of World Universities 2017 &#124; Top 500 universities &#124; Shanghai Ranking - 2017|website=www.shanghairanking.com}}</ref>\n| THE_W = 251\u2013300 | THE_W_ref =<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/world-ranking|title=World University Rankings|date=September 26, 2018|website=Times Higher Education (THE)}}</ref>\n| QS_W = 279 | QS_W_ref =<ref name=\"topuniversities.com\"/>\n}}\n\n*''[[The New York Times]]'': Among the World's 10 best universities by employer choice. Goethe University was ranked 10 out of 150 universities in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Companies Rank Universities|url=https://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2012/10/25/world/asia/25iht-sreducemerging25-graphic.html?ref=asia|work=New York Times|accessdate=1 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[ARWU]] World (Shanghai Rankings): 101-150<ref>{{cite web|title=Academic Ranking of World Universities 2017|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/ARWU2017.html|accessdate=3 Nov 2018}}</ref>\n* [[QS World University Rankings]]: 279<ref name=\"topuniversities.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2019|title=QS World University Rankings 2019|date=February 1, 2017|website=Top Universities}}</ref>\n\n==Points of interest==\n*[[Botanischer Garten der Goethe-Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main]], a [[botanical garden]]\n* [[IG Farben Building]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Germany}}\n* [[Frankfurt University Library]]\n* [[List of modern universities in Europe (1801\u20131945)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Goethe-Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main}}\n*[https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/en?locale=en University homepage] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{German U15}}\n{{Goethe University Frankfurt}}\n{{Universities in Germany}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Goethe University Frankfurt| ]]\n[[Category:Education in Frankfurt|University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1914]]\n[[Category:Universities in Germany]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Hesse]]\n[[Category:Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]\n[[Category:1914 establishments in Germany]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goethe_University}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Goethe University\n| native_name = Goethe-Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main\n| native_name_lang = deu\n| image = Logo-Goethe-University-Frankfurt-am-Main.svg\n| former_name = K\u00f6nigliche Universit\u00e4t zu Frankfurt am Main<ref name=\"2014_Neujahrsempfang\">{{cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/49212620/2014_Neujahrsempfang_StadtFrankfurt-Rede_Praesident.pdf |title=\"Aus der Mitte der Stadtgesellschaft \u2013 100 Jahre Goethe-Universit\u00e4t\" von Prof. Dr. Werner M\u00fcller-Esterl |language=German |accessdate=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n| established = {{start date|1914|10|18|df=y}}<ref name=\"2014_Neujahrsempfang\" />\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| budget = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 644.6&nbsp;Mio. <small>''(2018)''</small><ref name=\"jahresbericht_2018\">{{cite web|url=http://www.muk.uni-frankfurt.de/82141680.pdf |title=Jahrbuch 2018. \"Entwicklung gestalten\" |language=German |accessdate=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n| chancellor = [[Albrecht Fester]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muk.uni-frankfurt.de/70896808/060 |title=Goethe-Universit\u00e4t hat neuen Kanzler: Dr. Albrecht Fester \u00fcbernimmt das Amt an Hessens gr\u00f6\u00dfter Universit\u00e4t |language=German |date=2018-03-16 |accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n| president = [[Birgitta Wolff]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/36994074/praesidentin |title=Pr\u00e4sidentin der Goethe-Universit\u00e4t |language=German |accessdate=2016-05-27}}</ref>\n| vice-president = [[Simone Fulda]], [[Rolf van Dick]], [[Roger Erb]], [[Manfred Schubert-Zsilavecz]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/36994091/vizepraesidenten |title=Vizepr\u00e4sidenten der Goethe-Universit\u00e4t |language=German |accessdate=2018-09-10}}</ref>\n| faculty = 3,055.97 <small>''([[Full-time equivalent|FTE]], 2018)''</small><ref name=\"jahresbericht_2018\" />\n| administrative_staff = 2,038.56 <small>''([[Full-time equivalent|FTE]], 2018)''</small><ref name=\"jahresbericht_2018\" />\n| students = 46,325 <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uni-frankfurt.de/52565158 |title=Studierendenstatistik (Daten pro Semester) |language=German |accessdate=2020-02-22}}</ref>\n| undergrad = 21,366 <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\" />\n| postgrad = 7,169 <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\" />\n| doctoral = 1,664 <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\" />\n| other = 6,279 ([[teacher education]]) <small>''(2019)''</small><ref name=\"Studentenstatistik\" />\n| address = <small>Campus Westend:</small><br />Theodor-W.-Adorno-Platz&nbsp;1\n| city = [[Frankfurt am Main]]\n| state = [[Hessen]]\n| country = Germany\n| postcode = 60323\n| coor = {{Coord|50|7|40|N|8|40|00|E|type:edu_region:DE|display=inline,title}}\n| campus = multiple sites\n| language = [[German language|German]]\n| website = {{URL|1=http://www.goethe-university-frankfurt.de/|2=www.goethe-university-frankfurt.de}}\n| logo = HouseofFinance.jpg\n}}\n'''Goethe University''' ({{lang-de|Goethe-Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main}}) is a [[university]] located in [[Frankfurt am Main]], Germany. It was founded in 1914 as a citizens' university, which means it was founded and funded by the wealthy and active liberal citizenry of Frankfurt. The original name was '''Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main'''. In 1932, the university's name was extended in honour of one of the most famous native sons of Frankfurt, the poet, philosopher and writer/dramatist [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]. The university currently has around 45,000 students, distributed across four major campuses within the city.\n\nThe university celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2014. The first female president of the university, [[Birgitta Wolff]], was sworn into office in 2015.<ref name=\"Neue Uni-Pr\u00e4sidentin will kommunikativen F\u00fchrungsstil\">{{cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/rhein-main/frankfurt/frankfurt-neue-uni-praesidentin-birgitta-wolff-will-kommunikativen-fuehrungsstil-13319493.html|title=Neue Uni-Pr\u00e4sidentin will kommunikativen F\u00fchrungsstil|accessdate=2015-03-03|newspaper=Faz.net}}</ref> 20 [[List of Nobel laureates by university affiliation|Nobel Prize winners]] have been [[List of Nobel laureates by university affiliation#Other universities|affiliated with the university]], including [[Max von Laue]] and [[Max Born]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1914/laue.html|title=Nobel prize Physics laureates}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/39246655/nobelpreis?|title=Goethe-Universit\u00e4t \u2014 Nobelpreistr\u00e4ger an der Goethe Universit\u00e4t|website=www.uni-frankfurt.de|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref> The university is also affiliated with 18 winners of the prestigious [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/39246641/leibnizpreis?|title=Goethe-Universit\u00e4t \u2014 Leibnizpreistr\u00e4ger an der Goethe-Universit\u00e4t|website=www.uni-frankfurt.de|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nGoethe University is part of the [[IT cluster Rhine-Main-Neckar]]. The [[Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz]], the Goethe University Frankfurt and the [[Technische Universit\u00e4t Darmstadt]] together form the [[Rhine-Main-Universities]] (RMU).\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F005759-0014, Frankfurt-Main, Universit\u00e4t.jpg|thumb|Campus Bockenheim (in 1958)]]\n\nThe historical roots of the university can be traced back as far as 1484, when a City Council Library was established with a bequest from the patrician Ludwig von Marburg. Merged with other collections, it was renamed City Library in 1668 and became the university library in 1914. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ub.uni-frankfurt.de/ueber/stub_geschichte.html|title=Geschichte der Stadt- und Universit\u00e4tsbibliothek|website=www.ub.uni-frankfurt.de|access-date=2017-08-05}}</ref> Depending on the country, the date of foundation is recorded differently. According to Anglo-American calculations, the founding date of Goethe University would be 1484. In Germany, the date on which the right to award doctorates is granted is considered the founding year of a university.\n\nThe university has been best known historically for its [[Institute for Social Research]] (founded 1924), the institutional home of the [[Frankfurt School]], a preeminent 20th century school of [[philosophy]] and social thought. Some of the well-known scholars associated with this school include [[Theodor Adorno]], [[Max Horkheimer]], and [[J\u00fcrgen Habermas]], as well as [[Herbert Marcuse]], [[Erich Fromm]], and [[Walter Benjamin]] {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. Other well-known scholars at the University of Frankfurt include the sociologist [[Karl Mannheim]], the philosopher [[Hans-Georg Gadamer]], the philosophers of religion [[Franz Rosenzweig]], [[Martin Buber]], and [[Paul Tillich]], the psychologist [[Max Wertheimer]], and the sociologist [[Norbert Elias]] {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}.\nThe University of Frankfurt has at times been considered liberal, or left-leaning, and has had a reputation for [[Jew]]ish and [[Marxist]] (or even Jewish-Marxist) scholarship {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. During the [[Nazism|Nazi]] period, \"almost one third of its academics and many of its students were dismissed for racial and/or political reasons\u2014more than at any other German university\" {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. The university also played a major part in the [[German student movement]] of 1968.\n\nThe university also has been influential in the natural sciences and medicine, with Nobel Prize winners including [[Max von Laue]] and [[Max Born]], and breakthroughs such as the [[Stern\u2013Gerlach experiment]].\n\nIn recent years, the university has focused in particular on law, history, and economics, creating new institutes, such as the [[Institute for Law and Finance]] (ILF) and the [[Center for Financial Studies]] (CFS) {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. One of the university's ambitions is to become Germany's leading university for finance and economics, given the school's proximity to one of Europe's financial centers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.finance.uni-frankfurt.de/master/presse/178.pdf |title=Die Johann Wolfgang Goethe-Universit\u00e4t auf dem Weg zur f\u00fchrenden Wirtschaftshochschule in Deutschland |date= |accessdate=2011-09-26}}</ref> In cooperation with [[Duke University]]\u2019s [[Fuqua School of Business]], the [[Goethe Busines School]] offers an [[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]] program. Goethe University has established an international award for research in financial economics, the [[Deutsche bank prize|Deutsche Bank Prize in Financial Economics]].\n\n==Organization==\n[[File:Campus-westend-hoersaalgebaeude-hoersaal-2008-10-27-5.jpg|thumb|Campus Westend]]\n[[File:Bibliothek-westend-2005-10-27 1 (1).jpg|thumb|University Library at Campus Westend]]\n\nThe university consists of 16 faculties. Ordered by their sorting number, these are:<ref name=\"\u6cd5\u862d\u514b\u798f\u5927\u5b78\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.uni-frankfurt.de/43171422|title=Faculties|accessdate=2014-05-11}}</ref>\uff1a\n* 01. Rechtswissenschaft (Law)\n* 02. Wirtschaftswissenschaften (Economics and Business Administration)\n* 03. Gesellschaftswissenschaften (Social Sciences)\n* 04. Erziehungswissenschaften (Educational Sciences)\n* 05. Psychologie und Sportwissenschaften (Psychology and Sports Sciences)\n* 06. Evangelische Theologie (Protestant Theology)\n* 07. Katholische Theologie (Roman Catholic Theology)\n* 08. Philosophie und Geschichtswissenschaften (Philosophy and History)\n* 09. Sprach- und Kulturwissenschaften (Faculty of Linguistics, Cultures, and Arts)\n* 10. Neuere Philologien (Modern Languages)\n* 11. Geowissenschaften/Geographie (Geosciences and Geography)\n* 12. Informatik und Mathematik (Computer Science and Mathematics)\n* 13. Physik (Physics)\n* 14. Biochemie, Chemie und Pharmazie (Biochemistry, Chemistry and Pharmacy)\n* 15. Biowissenschaften (Biological Sciences)\n* 16. Medizin (Medical Science)\n\nIn addition, there are several co-located research institutes of the [[Max Planck Society]]:\n* [[Max Planck Institute of Biophysics]]\n* [[Max Planck Institute for Brain Research]]\n* [[Max Planck Institute for European Legal History]]\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Campus Westend Frankfurt 01.jpg|thumb|Campus Westend]]\n[[File:Campus-westend-park-am-poelzig-bau-2008-05-05-2.jpg|thumb|Campus Westend]]\n\nThe University is located across four campuses in Frankfurt am Main:\n\n* '''Campus Westend''': \nHeadquarters of the university, also housing Social sciences, Pedagogy, Psychology, Theology, Philosophy, History, Philology, Archaeology, Law, Economics and Business Administration, Human geography\n\n* '''Campus Bockenheim''': \nUniversity library, Mathematics, Computer science, Art history, Fine Arts\n\n* '''Campus Riedberg''': \nPharmacy, Physics, Chemistry, Biochemistry, Biology, Geosciences and Geography\n\n* '''Campus Niederrad''': \nMedical science, Dentistry, University hospital\n\n* '''Campus Ginnheim:'''\n\nSports.\n\n===Campus Westend===\n[[File:IG Farben Gebaeude Uni Frankfurt.jpg|thumb|[[IG Farben Building]] at Uni Frankfurt|500px]]\n[[File:Goethe University Frankfurt Poelzig Building.jpeg|thumb|[[IG Farben Building]] at ''Campus Westend'']]\n\u201cCampus Westend\u201d of the University is dominated by the [[IG Farben Building]] by architect Hans Poelzig, an example of the [[Modern architecture|modernist]] [[New Objectivity]] style.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.monumente-online.de/de/ausgaben/2007/5/das-uebertuenchte-arkadien.php|title=Ein Wandgem\u00e4lde in Frankfurts Universit\u00e4t - Monumente Online|website=www.monumente-online.de}}</ref><ref>M. Tafuri, F. Dal Co: Klassische Moderne, Stuttgart, 1988, S148f</ref> The style for the IG Farben Building was originally chosen as \"a symbol for the scientific and mercantile German manpower, made out of iron and stone\", as the [[IG Farben]] director at the time of construction, [[Georg von Schnitzler|Baron von Schnitzler]], stated in his opening speech in October 1930.\n\nAfter the university took over the complex, new buildings were added to the campus. On 30 May 2008, the [[House of Finance]] relocated to a new building designed by the architects Kleihues+Kleihues, following the style of the IG Farben Building. The upper floors of the House of Finance building have several separate offices as well as shared office space for researchers and students. The ground floor is open to the public and welcomes visitors with a spacious, naturally lit foyer that leads to lecture halls, seminar rooms, and the information center, a 24-hour reference library. The ground floor also accommodates computer rooms and a caf\u00e9. The floors, walls and ceiling of the foyer are decorated with a grid design that is continued throughout the entire building. The flooring is inspired by Raphael's mural, ''The School of Athens''.\n\n==Goethe Business School==\nThe [[Goethe Business School]] is a graduate business school at the university, established in 2004, part of the House of Finance at the Westend Campus and the IKB building. it is a non-profit foundation under private law held by the university. The Chairman of the Board at Goethe Business School, Rolf E. Breuer, is former Chairman of the Supervisory Board of [[Deutsche Bank]] {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}. Goethe Business School has a partnership in Executive Education with the [[Indian School of Business]] (ISB) in Hyderabad {{citation needed|date=January 2014}}.\n\n==The Deutsche Bank Prize==\nThe [[Deutsche Bank Prize in Financial Economics]] honors renowned researchers who have made influential contributions to the fields of finance and money and macroeconomics, and whose work has led to practical and policy-relevant results. It is awarded biannually, since 2005, by the [[Center for Financial Studies]], in partnership with Goethe University Frankfurt. The award carries an endowment of \u20ac50,000, which is donated by the Stiftungsfonds Deutsche Bank im Stifterverband f\u00fcr die Deutsche Wissenschaft.\n\n==Notable faculty (partial list)==\n* [[Theodor W. Adorno]] (1903\u20131969), double Ordinarius of philosophy and sociology and member of the [[Frankfurt School]]\n* [[Max Horkheimer]], member of the [[Frankfurt School]]\n* [[J\u00fcrgen Habermas]], sociologist and a philosopher\n* [[Hans Bethe]], theoretical physicist (Nobel Prize 1967)\n* [[Max Born]], theoretical physicist and mathematician (Nobel Prize 1954)\n* [[Klaus Bringmann]], historian\n* [[Rolf van Dick]], social psychologist\n* [[Paul Ehrlich]], Nobel Prize Winner 1908\n* [[Walter Gerlach]], theoretical physicist\n* [[Walter Hallstein]] (1901\u20131982), first [[President of the European Commission]]\n* [[Helmut Kiener]], psychologist turned investment professional, founder of the [[ponzi scheme]] [[K1 fund]]\n* [[Vladimir Ko\u0161ak]], economist, lawyer, politician and diplomat\n* [[Josef Mengele]], officer and a physician in the [[Nazi concentration camp]] [[Auschwitz]]\n* [[Oskar Dirlewanger]], officer, who served as the founder and commander of the infamous Nazi SS penal unit \"[[36th Waffen Grenadier Division of the SS|Dirlewanger]]\" during World War II\n* [[Boudewijn Sirks]], Professor of the History of Ancient Law from 1997 to 2005, later [[Regius Professor of Civil Law (Oxford)|Regius Professor of Civil Law]] at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]\n* [[Walter Greiner]], theoretical physicist in high energy physics\n* [[Alfred Schmidt (philosopher)|Alfred Schmidt]], philosopher and translator\n* [[Horst St\u00f6cker]], theoretical physicist\n* [[Alexander R. Todd, Baron Todd]], chemist\n* [[Moses Rothschild]], innovator\n* [[Luciano Rezzolla]], theoretical astrophysicist\n\n==Nobel Prize winners (alumni and faculty)==\n* [[Paul Ehrlich]]: 1908 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\n* [[Max von Laue]]: 1914 Nobel Prize for Physics<ref>{{cite web|title=Nobel Prize Goethe University|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/physics/laureates/1914/laue.html|accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n* [[Otto Loewi]]: 1914 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine<ref>{{cite web|title=Loewi, Otto|url=http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz54009.html|website=Deutsche Biographie|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Karrer]]: 1937 Nobel Prize for Chemistry\n* [[Otto Stern]]: 1943 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[Max Born]]: 1954 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[Alexander Robertus Todd]]: 1957 Nobel Prize for Chemistry\n* [[Karl Ziegler]]: 1963 Nobel Prize for Chemistry\n* [[Hans Bethe]]: 1967 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[Niels Kaj Jerne]]: 1984 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine<ref name=\"nobellist\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/39246655/nobelpreis|title=Goethe-Universit\u00e4t \u2014 Nobelpreistr\u00e4ger an der Goethe Universit\u00e4t|website=www.uni-frankfurt.de}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Niels K. Jerne - Biographical|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/medicine/laureates/1984/jerne-bio.html|accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n* [[Gerd Binnig]]: 1986 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[Jean-Marie Lehn]]: 1987 Nobel Prize for Chemistry<ref name=\"nobellist\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Marie Pierre Lehn - Curriculum Vitae|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1987/lehn-cv.html|accessdate=2016-03-11}}</ref>\n* [[Hartmut Michel]]: 1988 Nobel Prize for Chemistry\n* [[Reinhard Selten]]: 1994 Nobel Prize for Economics\n* [[Christiane N\u00fcsslein-Volhard]]: 1995 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\n* [[Horst Ludwig St\u00f6rmer]]: 1998 Nobel Prize for Physics\n* [[G\u00fcnter Blobel]]: 1999 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\n* [[Peter Gr\u00fcnberg]]: 2007 Nobel Prize for Physics\n\n==World rankings==\n{{Infobox European university ranking\n| ARWU_W = 101-150 | ARWU_W_ref = <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/ARWU2017.html|title=ARWU World University Rankings 2017 &#124; Academic Ranking of World Universities 2017 &#124; Top 500 universities &#124; Shanghai Ranking - 2017|website=www.shanghairanking.com}}</ref>\n| THE_W = 251\u2013300 | THE_W_ref =<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/world-ranking|title=World University Rankings|date=September 26, 2018|website=Times Higher Education (THE)}}</ref>\n| QS_W = 279 | QS_W_ref =<ref name=\"topuniversities.com\"/>\n}}\n\n*''[[The New York Times]]'': Among the World's 10 best universities by employer choice. Goethe University was ranked 10 out of 150 universities in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Companies Rank Universities|url=https://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2012/10/25/world/asia/25iht-sreducemerging25-graphic.html?ref=asia|work=New York Times|accessdate=1 December 2012}}</ref>\n*[[ARWU]] World (Shanghai Rankings): 101-150<ref>{{cite web|title=Academic Ranking of World Universities 2017|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/ARWU2017.html|accessdate=3 Nov 2018}}</ref>\n* [[QS World University Rankings]]: 279<ref name=\"topuniversities.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2019|title=QS World University Rankings 2019|date=February 1, 2017|website=Top Universities}}</ref>\n\n==Points of interest==\n*[[Botanischer Garten der Goethe-Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main]], a [[botanical garden]]\n* [[IG Farben Building]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Germany}}\n* [[Frankfurt University Library]]\n* [[List of modern universities in Europe (1801\u20131945)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Goethe-Universit\u00e4t Frankfurt am Main}}\n*[https://www.uni-frankfurt.de/en?locale=en University homepage] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{German U15}}\n{{Goethe University Frankfurt}}\n{{Universities in Germany}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Goethe University Frankfurt| ]]\n[[Category:Education in Frankfurt|University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1914]]\n[[Category:Universities in Germany]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Hesse]]\n[[Category:Johann Wolfgang von Goethe]]\n[[Category:1914 establishments in Germany]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goethe_University}}\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goethe_University_Frankfurt"}
{"title_page": "Morgan Aero 8", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image = File:2006 SAG - Morgan aero 8 -03.jpg\n| caption = Morgan Aero 8 (march 2006)\n| name = Morgan Aero 8\n| manufacturer = [[Morgan Motor Company]]\n| production = 2001\u20132010<br>2015\u20132019\n| designer = Matthew Humphries\n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-Segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[convertible (car)|convertible]]\n| layout = \n| engine = 4.4 L [[V8 engine|V8]] [[BMW N62|N62]]<br/>4.8 L V8 [[BMW N62|N62]]\n| weight = 1180 kg (2596 lb)\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| wheelbase = 100 in (2530 mm)\n| width = 69 in (1770 mm)\n| length = 162 in (4120 mm)\n}}\nThe '''Morgan Aero 8''' is a [[Sports car|sports]] [[automobile|car]] built by [[Morgan Motor Company]] at its factory in [[Malvern Link]], [[England]] (an area of [[Malvern, Worcestershire|Malvern]] in [[Worcestershire]]) and designed by the firm's designer Matthew Humphries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-review/morgan/aero-8|title=Morgan Aero 8 Review (2018) {{!}} Autocar|website=www.autocar.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe Aero 8 is notable for several reasons, primarily because it is the first new Morgan design since 1964's [[Morgan +4+|+4+]]. It does not use [[anti-roll bar]]s, an oddity in a modern sporting car. It is also the first Morgan vehicle with an aluminium chassis and frame as opposed to traditional Morgan vehicles (\"trads\") that have an aluminium skinned wooden body tub on a steel chassis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/car/01q2/morgan_aero_8-first_drive_review |title=Morgan Aero 8 \u2013 First Drive Review \u2013 Auto Reviews |publisher=Car and Driver |date= |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>\n\nThe engine first powering the Aero 8 was a 4.4&nbsp;L [[BMW M62]] [[V8 engine|V8]] mated to a 6-speed [[Getrag]] transmission. In 2007, the Series 4 Aero 8 was released which had an upgraded 4.8&nbsp;L [[BMW N62]] [[V8 engine|V8]] with an optional [[ZF_Friedrichshafen|ZF]] automatic transmission. All Aero 8s are assembled at Morgan's Malvern Link factory, where they are able to produce up to 14 cars a week (Aeros and trads).\n\nIt has been criticized for its \"crosseyed\" look<ref name=\"Ref_\">{{cite web |url=http://car-reviews.automobile.com/news/morgan-revives-4-seat-roadster-improves-aero-8/1748/ |title=Morgan Revives 4-Seat Roadster, Improves Aero 8 &#124; Morgan Auto Newss &#124; Automobile.com |publisher=Car-reviews.automobile.com |accessdate=2009-05-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012045847/http://car-reviews.automobile.com/news/morgan-revives-4-seat-roadster-improves-aero-8/1748/ |archivedate=12 October 2008  }}</ref> which originally was justified by the manufacturers as conferring aerodynamic benefits.<ref name=AutoMotorundSport200025>{{cite journal| authorlink = Bernd Stegemann | title = Aero flott: Mit dem neuen Morgan Aero 8 ist der britische Kleinhersteller in der Gegenwart gekommen.  Der leichte Alu-Roadster mit dem 286-PS-V8 von BMW verbindet moderne Technik mit traditioneller Form und Machart | journal = [[Auto, Motor und Sport]]| volume = Heft 25 2000| pages = Pages 52\u201354|date = 29 November 2000}}</ref> In response, Morgan changed the design for 2007 and later cars to a front end design based on the Morgan Aeromax, using Mini rather than VW New Beetle headlights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/carreviews/newreviews/207206/morgan_aero_8.html |title=Morgan Aero 8 &#124; New Reviews &#124; Car Reviews |publisher=Auto Express |date=2007-01-11 |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>\n\n==Morgan AeroMax==\n[[File:MorganAeroMax.jpg|thumb|right|Morgan AeroMax, pictured in [[London]], showing the distinctive 'boat tail' rear]]\n[[File:2015 Morgan Aero Supersports Automatic 4.8 Front.jpg|thumb|right|Morgan Aero SuperSports]]\nThe Morgan Aeromax is the coupe variation of the Aero 8. Production, which was undertaken in 2008 and 2009, was limited to one hundred cars,<ref name=\"Ref_a\">[http://www.morgancars.com.au/ Morgan Products] Retrieved on 20 November 2010</ref> each costing \u00a3110,000. Owners have included [[Richard Hammond]], [[Rowan Atkinson]] and [[Paul O'Grady]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} Taillights of AeroMax and Super Sports were borrowed from [[Lancia Thesis]].\n\n==Morgan Aero SuperSports==\nThe Morgan Aero SuperSports is a [[Targa top|targa-roofed]] version of the AeroMax, sharing its bonded aluminium chassis and lower bodywork with the coupe.<ref name=\"Ref_b\">[http://www.autocar.co.uk/CarReviews/FirstDrives/Morgan-Aero-Supersports-V8-Supersports-auto/251830/ Morgan Aero Supersports review] Retrieved on 20 November 2010</ref>\n\n==New Morgan Aero 8==\nAt the [[Geneva Motor Show#2015|Geneva Motor Show]] in March 2015 Morgan announced that the Morgan Aero 8 would be revived with a new model. This has since been discontinued in 2019.\n\n==Specifications==\n\n===Powertrain===\nThe Aero 8's engine is BMW's dual overhead cam [[BMW N62|N62]] V8, in either 4.4&nbsp;L or 4.8&nbsp;L displacements. The former's output is {{convert|334|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} and {{convert|450|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}, while the latter's is {{Convert|367|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6000 rpm and {{Convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 3600 rpm. The engine is paired with either a [[Getrag]] 6-speed manual or [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] 6-speed automatic transmission.\n\n[[File:Morgan Aero 8 rear.jpg|thumb|Modern MorganAero 8 rear]]\n[[File:Morgan Aero 8 badge.jpg|thumb|Modern MorganAero 8 badge]]\n\n===Chassis===\nThe chassis is an ultra-stiff aluminum alloy. Suspension is fully [[Independent suspension|Independent]], with Eibach coil springs, fully floating in the rear, over Koni shock absorbers. Brakes are cast iron [[Disc brake|discs]], with 6-pot calipers at the front and 2-pot calipers at the rear.\n\n===Performance===\n{{Listen|type=sound|filename=Morgan Aero Supersports recorded2010.ogg|title=Morgan Aero Supersports at Goodwood Festival of Speed 2010}}\nFor Version IV of the car, top speed is an estimated {{convert|170|mph|km/h||abbr=on}} and 0 to 100&nbsp;km/h (62&nbsp;mph) is done in 4.3 seconds for the manual transmission and 4.1 seconds for the automatic.\n\n==Motorsport==\n[[File:Morgan Aero 8 GT3 Nr31 Oschersleben2008.jpg|right|thumb|Morgan Aero 8 GT3 at [[Motopark Oschersleben]]]]\nThe Aero 8 has competed at the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] twice, in [[2002 24 Hours of Le Mans|2002]] and [[2004 24 Hours of Le Mans|2004]]. There have also been several entries in the [[FIA GT]] series from both works cars and privateers. It is also used in the [[British GT]] Series. It is currently racing in the FIA GT3 European championship and has proven competitive. The [https://web.archive.org/web/20080316013453/http://www.racecar-engineering.com/articles/sportscar/169806/morgan-gt3.html Aero 8 GT3] car is built by AUTO GT. The Aero 8 was also used in the [[2003 Bathurst 24 Hour]] scoring a DNF with a rare BMW engine failure and the [[2004 12 Hours of Sebring]] finishing 20th outright and 10th in the GT class.\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Holmes-UltConv | pages=120\u2013121}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Morgan Aero 8}}\n* [http://www.morgan-motor.co.uk/aero8/ Morgan Motor Company's Aero 8 webpage]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Morgan Motor Company}}\n\n[[Category:Morgan vehicles|Aero 8]]\n[[Category:Grand tourers]]\n[[Category:Retro-style automobiles]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2000]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans race cars]]\n[[Category:2010s cars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| image = File:2006 SAG - Morgan aero 8 -03.jpg\n| caption = Morgan Aero 8 (march 2006)\n| name = Morgan Aero 8\n| manufacturer = [[Morgan Motor Company]]\n| production = 2001\u20132010<br>2015\u20132019\n| designer = Matthew Humphries\n| class = [[Sports car]] ([[S-Segment|S]])\n| body_style = 2-door [[convertible (car)|convertible]]\n| layout = \n| engine = 4.4 L [[V8 engine|V8]] [[BMW N62|N62]]<br/>4.8 L V8 [[BMW N62|N62]]\n| weight = 1180 kg (2596 lb)\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| wheelbase = 100 in (2530 mm)\n| width = 69 in (1770 mm)\n| length = 162 in (4120 mm)\n}}\nThe '''Morgan Aero 8''' is a [[Sports car|sports]] [[automobile|car]] built by [[Morgan Motor Company]] at its factory in [[Malvern Link]], [[England]] (an area of [[Malvern, Worcestershire|Malvern]] in [[Worcestershire]]) and designed by the firm's designer Matthew Humphries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-review/morgan/aero-8|title=Morgan Aero 8 Review (2018) {{!}} Autocar|website=www.autocar.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref>\n\nThe Aero 8 is notable for several reasons, primarily because it is the first new Morgan design since 1964's [[Morgan +4+|+4+]]. It does not use [[anti-roll bar]]s, an oddity in a modern sporting car. It is also the first Morgan vehicle with an aluminium chassis and frame as opposed to traditional Morgan vehicles (\"trads\") that have an aluminium skinned wooden body tub on a steel chassis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caranddriver.com/reviews/car/01q2/morgan_aero_8-first_drive_review |title=Morgan Aero 8 \u2013 First Drive Review \u2013 Auto Reviews |publisher=Car and Driver |date= |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>\n\nThe engine first powering the Aero 8 was a 4.4&nbsp;L [[BMW M62]] [[V8 engine|V8]] mated to a 6-speed [[Getrag]] transmission. In 2007, the Series 4 Aero 8 was released which had an upgraded 4.8&nbsp;L [[BMW N62]] [[V8 engine|V8]] with an optional [[ZF_Friedrichshafen|ZF]] automatic transmission. All Aero 8s are assembled at Morgan's Malvern Link factory, where they are able to produce up to 14 cars a week (Aeros and trads).\n\nIt has been criticized for its \"crosseyed\" look<ref name=\"Ref_\">{{cite web |url=http://car-reviews.automobile.com/news/morgan-revives-4-seat-roadster-improves-aero-8/1748/ |title=Morgan Revives 4-Seat Roadster, Improves Aero 8 &#124; Morgan Auto Newss &#124; Automobile.com |publisher=Car-reviews.automobile.com |accessdate=2009-05-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012045847/http://car-reviews.automobile.com/news/morgan-revives-4-seat-roadster-improves-aero-8/1748/ |archivedate=12 October 2008  }}</ref> which originally was justified by the manufacturers as conferring aerodynamic benefits.<ref name=AutoMotorundSport200025>{{cite journal| authorlink = Bernd Stegemann | title = Aero flott: Mit dem neuen Morgan Aero 8 ist der britische Kleinhersteller in der Gegenwart gekommen.  Der leichte Alu-Roadster mit dem 286-PS-V8 von BMW verbindet moderne Technik mit traditioneller Form und Machart | journal = [[Auto, Motor und Sport]]| volume = Heft 25 2000| pages = Pages 52\u201354|date = 29 November 2000}}</ref> In response, Morgan changed the design for 2007 and later cars to a front end design based on the Morgan Aeromax, using Mini rather than VW New Beetle headlights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoexpress.co.uk/carreviews/newreviews/207206/morgan_aero_8.html |title=Morgan Aero 8 &#124; New Reviews &#124; Car Reviews |publisher=Auto Express |date=2007-01-11 |accessdate=2011-09-17}}</ref>\n\n==Morgan AeroMax==\n[[File:MorganAeroMax.jpg|thumb|right|Morgan AeroMax, pictured in [[London]], showing the distinctive 'boat tail' rear]]\n[[File:2015 Morgan Aero Supersports Automatic 4.8 Front.jpg|thumb|right|Morgan Aero SuperSports]]\nThe Morgan Aeromax is the coupe variation of the Aero 8. Production, which was undertaken in 2008 and 2009, was limited to one hundred cars,<ref name=\"Ref_a\">[http://www.morgancars.com.au/ Morgan Products] Retrieved on 20 November 2010</ref> each costing \u00a3110,000. Owners have included [[Richard Hammond]], [[Rowan Atkinson]] and [[Paul O'Grady]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} Taillights of AeroMax and Super Sports were borrowed from [[Lancia Thesis]].\n\n==Morgan Aero SuperSports==\nThe Morgan Aero SuperSports is a [[Targa top|targa-roofed]] version of the AeroMax, sharing its bonded aluminium chassis and lower bodywork with the coupe.<ref name=\"Ref_b\">[http://www.autocar.co.uk/CarReviews/FirstDrives/Morgan-Aero-Supersports-V8-Supersports-auto/251830/ Morgan Aero Supersports review] Retrieved on 20 November 2010</ref>\n\n==New Morgan Aero 8==\nAt the [[Geneva Motor Show#2015|Geneva Motor Show]] in March 2015 Morgan announced that the Morgan Aero 8 would be revived with a new model. This has since been discontinued in 2019.\n\n==Specifications==\n\n===Powertrain===\nThe Aero 8's engine is BMW's dual overhead cam [[BMW N62|N62]] V8, in either 4.4&nbsp;L or 4.8&nbsp;L displacements. The former's output is {{convert|334|PS|kW hp|abbr=on}} and {{convert|450|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}}, while the latter's is {{Convert|367|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 6000 rpm and {{Convert|490|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 3600 rpm. The engine is paired with either a [[Getrag]] 6-speed manual or [[ZF Friedrichshafen|ZF]] 6-speed automatic transmission.\n\n[[File:Morgan Aero 8 rear.jpg|thumb|Modern MorganAero 8 rear]]\n[[File:Morgan Aero 8 badge.jpg|thumb|Modern MorganAero 8 badge]]\n\n===Chassis===\nThe chassis is an ultra-stiff aluminum alloy. Suspension is fully [[Independent suspension|Independent]], with Eibach coil springs, fully floating in the rear, over Koni shock absorbers. Brakes are cast iron [[Disc brake|discs]], with 6-pot calipers at the front and 2-pot calipers at the rear.\n\n===Performance===\n{{Listen|type=sound|filename=Morgan Aero Supersports recorded2010.ogg|title=Morgan Aero Supersports at Goodwood Festival of Speed 2010}}\nFor Version IV of the car, top speed is an estimated {{convert|170|mph|km/h||abbr=on}} and 0 to 100&nbsp;km/h (62&nbsp;mph) is done in 4.3 seconds for the manual transmission and 4.1 seconds for the automatic.\n\n==Motorsport==\n[[File:Morgan Aero 8 GT3 Nr31 Oschersleben2008.jpg|right|thumb|Morgan Aero 8 GT3 at [[Motopark Oschersleben]]]]\nThe Aero 8 has competed at the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]] twice, in [[2002 24 Hours of Le Mans|2002]] and [[2004 24 Hours of Le Mans|2004]]. There have also been several entries in the [[FIA GT]] series from both works cars and privateers. It is also used in the [[British GT]] Series. It is currently racing in the FIA GT3 European championship and has proven competitive. The [https://web.archive.org/web/20080316013453/http://www.racecar-engineering.com/articles/sportscar/169806/morgan-gt3.html Aero 8 GT3] car is built by AUTO GT. The Aero 8 was also used in the [[2003 Bathurst 24 Hour]] scoring a DNF with a rare BMW engine failure and the [[2004 12 Hours of Sebring]] finishing 20th outright and 10th in the GT class.\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Holmes-UltConv | pages=120\u2013121}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Morgan Aero 8}}\n* [http://www.morgan-motor.co.uk/aero8/ Morgan Motor Company's Aero 8 webpage]\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n\n{{Morgan Motor Company}}\n\n[[Category:Morgan vehicles|Aero 8]]\n[[Category:Grand tourers]]\n[[Category:Retro-style automobiles]]\n[[Category:Rear-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2000]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans race cars]]\n", "name_user": "TKOIII", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morgan_Aero_8"}
{"title_page": "Queen Mary's Hospital, Sidcup", "text_new": "{{see also|Queen Mary's Hospital, Roehampton}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Queen Mary's Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[Oxleas NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| Image       = Day nursery, Queen Mary's Hospital, Sidcup, Kent - geograph.org.uk - 152871.jpg\n| Caption     = Queen Mary Hospital's Day Nursery\n| map_type    = United Kingdom London Bexley\n| map_caption = Location within London Borough of Bexley\n| Logo        =\n| Logo Size   =\n| Location    = [[Sidcup]]\n| Region      = [[London]]\n| State       = \n| Country     = [[England]]\n| Coordinates = {{coord|51.4189|0.1014|display=inline,title}}\n| HealthCare  = [[National Health Service (England)|NHS England]]\n| Type        = District General\n| Speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (ie not a broad spectrum of specialities) and Type=Specialist/Teaching -->\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = No\n| Affiliation = <!-- 'None' or Medical School and University affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| Patron      =\n| Beds        = 430\n| Founded     = 1917\n| Closed      =\n| Website     = {{URL|qmh.oxleas.nhs.uk}}\n}}\n'''Queen Mary's Hospital''' is an acute district general hospital in [[Sidcup]], [[South London|South East London]], serving the population of the [[London Borough of Bexley]]. It was once administered by Queen Mary's Sidcup NHS Trust established in 1993.\n\nFollowing the dissolution of the [[South London Healthcare NHS Trust]] in 2013 it came under the management of [[Oxleas NHS Foundation Trust]], with other services being provided by [[King's College Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]], [[Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trust]], [[Dartford and Gravesham NHS Trust]] and [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Hospital is served by a number of bus routes, including routes: 229, 286, B14 and R11 serving the hospital directly,  providing links to [[Albany Park, Bexley|Albany Park]], [[Bexleyheath]], [[Sidcup]], [[St Mary Cray|St Mary Cray,]] [[Orpington]], [[Green Street Green|Green Street Green,]] [[Eltham]], [[Kidbrooke]], [[Westcombe Park railway station|Westcombe Park Station]], [[Greenwich]], [[Bexley]], [[Barnehurst]], [[Abbey Wood]] and [[Thamesmead]]. Routes B14 and 286 serve a circular route around the hospital serving bus stops at the Cancer Unit and the Main Enterance, while routes 229, 286 and R11 use the hospital as a terminus.\n\nRoutes 160 and 269 also serve the hospital from bus stops on Chislehurst Road, providing further links to [[Chislehurst]], [[Bickley]], [[Bromley]], [[New Eltham]] and [[Catford]].\n\nThe nearest railway stations to the hospital include [[Sidcup railway station|Sidcup]] and [[Chislehurst railway station|Chislehurst]] Stations.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Sir Harold Delf Gillies Plaque Queen Mary's Hospital Sidcup.jpg|thumb|left|300px|A plaque commemorating Sir Harold Gillies' contribution to Plastic Surgery]]\nThe Queen's Hospital was opened in prefabricated buildings in the grounds of [[Frognal House]] in August 1917.<ref name=lost>{{cite web|url=https://ezitis.myzen.co.uk/queenmarysidcup.html|title=Queen Mary's Hospital, Sidcup|publisher=Lost Hospitals of London|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> It provided pioneering plastic surgery under the guidance of [[Harold Gillies|Sir Harold Gillies]] to soldiers sustaining facial injuries during [[World War I|First World War]].<ref name=lost/>\n\nIt was re-opened as a general hospital known as \"Queen Mary's Hospital\" by [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]] in 1930.<ref name=lost/> It was damaged by bombing during [[World War II]] and joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948.<ref name=lost/> The prefabricated buildings were replaced by more permanent structures between 1962 and 1974.<ref name=lost/>\n\nIn April 2009 three NHS Trusts merged, those of Queen Mary's Sidcup, Queen Elizabeth Hospital and Bromley Hospitals as the multi-site South London Healthcare NHS Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/90-000-salary-for-debt-ridden-trust-1-580194|title=\u00a390,000 salary for debt-ridden Trust|publisher=Bromley Times|date=27 May 2009|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010 the hospital's A & E Department temporarily closed and the maternity services in the Kent Women's Wing. Acute services were transferred to the two sister hospitals, the [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Woolwich]] and the [[Princess Royal University Hospital]] in [[Farnborough, London|Farnborough]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/kent/hi/people_and_places/newsid_9310000/9310492.stm|title=Half of Darent Valley A&E patients do not need A&E|publisher=BBC|date=22 December 2010|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, the merged Trust was dissolved, and the hospital split between various other trusts. Oxleas NHS Foundation Trust became the owner of the estate and took responsibility for the running of some clinical services. King's College Hospital NHS Foundation Trust and Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trust became responsible for running other clinical services at the hospital.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slh.nhs.uk/ |title=Welcome|publisher=South London Healthcare NHS Trust|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081211192117/http://www.qms.nhs.uk/aboutus/history-and-archives.aspx Queen Mary's Hospital Sidcup]\n* [http://www.nhs.uk/Services/Hospitals/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=2857 NHS Choice Page]\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1917]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1974]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in London]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Bexley]]\n[[Category:Sidcup]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|Queen Mary's Hospital, Roehampton}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Queen Mary's Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[Oxleas NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| Image       = Day nursery, Queen Mary's Hospital, Sidcup, Kent - geograph.org.uk - 152871.jpg\n| Caption     = Queen Mary Hospital's Day Nursery\n| map_type    = United Kingdom London Bexley\n| map_caption = Location within London Borough of Bexley\n| Logo        =\n| Logo Size   =\n| Location    = [[Sidcup]]\n| Region      = [[London]]\n| State       = \n| Country     = [[England]]\n| Coordinates = {{coord|51.4189|0.1014|display=inline,title}}\n| HealthCare  = [[National Health Service (England)|NHS England]]\n| Type        = District General\n| Speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (ie not a broad spectrum of specialities) and Type=Specialist/Teaching -->\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = No\n| Affiliation = <!-- 'None' or Medical School and University affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| Patron      =\n| Beds        = 430\n| Founded     = 1917\n| Closed      =\n| Website     = {{URL|qmh.oxleas.nhs.uk}}\n}}\n'''Queen Mary's Hospital''' is an acute district general hospital in [[Sidcup]], [[South London|South East London]], serving the population of the [[London Borough of Bexley]]. It was once administered by Queen Mary's Sidcup NHS Trust established in 1993.\n\nFollowing the dissolution of the [[South London Healthcare NHS Trust]] in 2013 it came under the management of [[Oxleas NHS Foundation Trust]], with other services being provided by [[King's College Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]], [[Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trust]], [[Dartford and Gravesham NHS Trust]] and [[Guy's and St Thomas' NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Sir Harold Delf Gillies Plaque Queen Mary's Hospital Sidcup.jpg|thumb|left|300px|A plaque commemorating Sir Harold Gillies' contribution to Plastic Surgery]]\nThe Queen's Hospital was opened in prefabricated buildings in the grounds of [[Frognal House]] in August 1917.<ref name=lost>{{cite web|url=https://ezitis.myzen.co.uk/queenmarysidcup.html|title=Queen Mary's Hospital, Sidcup|publisher=Lost Hospitals of London|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> It provided pioneering plastic surgery under the guidance of [[Harold Gillies|Sir Harold Gillies]] to soldiers sustaining facial injuries during [[World War I|First World War]].<ref name=lost/>\n\nIt was re-opened as a general hospital known as \"Queen Mary's Hospital\" by [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]] in 1930.<ref name=lost/> It was damaged by bombing during [[World War II]] and joined the [[National Health Service]] in 1948.<ref name=lost/> The prefabricated buildings were replaced by more permanent structures between 1962 and 1974.<ref name=lost/>\n\nIn April 2009 three NHS Trusts merged, those of Queen Mary's Sidcup, Queen Elizabeth Hospital and Bromley Hospitals as the multi-site South London Healthcare NHS Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bromleytimes.co.uk/news/90-000-salary-for-debt-ridden-trust-1-580194|title=\u00a390,000 salary for debt-ridden Trust|publisher=Bromley Times|date=27 May 2009|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2010 the hospital's A & E Department temporarily closed and the maternity services in the Kent Women's Wing. Acute services were transferred to the two sister hospitals, the [[Queen Elizabeth Hospital, Woolwich]] and the [[Princess Royal University Hospital]] in [[Farnborough, London|Farnborough]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/kent/hi/people_and_places/newsid_9310000/9310492.stm|title=Half of Darent Valley A&E patients do not need A&E|publisher=BBC|date=22 December 2010|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, the merged Trust was dissolved, and the hospital split between various other trusts. Oxleas NHS Foundation Trust became the owner of the estate and took responsibility for the running of some clinical services. King's College Hospital NHS Foundation Trust and Lewisham and Greenwich NHS Trust became responsible for running other clinical services at the hospital.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slh.nhs.uk/ |title=Welcome|publisher=South London Healthcare NHS Trust|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081211192117/http://www.qms.nhs.uk/aboutus/history-and-archives.aspx Queen Mary's Hospital Sidcup]\n* [http://www.nhs.uk/Services/Hospitals/Overview/DefaultView.aspx?id=2857 NHS Choice Page]\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1917]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1974]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in London]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Bexley]]\n[[Category:Sidcup]]\n", "name_user": "Trisytan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added bus and train links at Queen Mary's Hospital", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen_Mary%27s_Hospital,_Sidcup"}
